    <p>The difference in energy cost between the two types is modest at small scales. What matters more for planetary mixers is the increased motor wear and servicing cost when they're used for heavy bread dough work beyond their design intent. A planetary mixer used primarily for cakes and light tasks will have a much longer service life than one pressed into heavy daily bread dough mixing.</p>

    <h2>6. Ease of Cleaning</h2>

    <h3>Planetary Mixer: Easy to Clean</h3>
    <p>The bowl on a planetary mixer lifts out completely, making it easy to wash at a sink or in a commercial dishwasher. The three standard attachments (whisk, flat beater, dough hook) also detach easily and can be washed separately. The mixer head itself rarely gets contaminated — cleaning is typically just the bowl and the attachment.</p>
    <p>For bakeries making multiple products through the day (switching between batter and dough, for example), the ease of cleaning between batches is a real operational advantage. A planetary mixer can be cleaned in 5–7 minutes between product types.</p>

    <h3>Spiral Mixer: Moderate Cleaning Effort</h3>
    <p>Most spiral mixers have a fixed bowl — it doesn't detach. You clean it in place. The spiral hook and bowl guard typically do detach for cleaning, but the bowl itself needs to be scrubbed at the machine. Higher-end spiral mixers have a removable bowl, but these are more expensive. For a single-product bread operation, this isn't a problem — you're only cleaning dough residue, which scrapes off cleanly once dry or can be rinsed while the bowl is still warm.</p>
    <p>Cleaning a fixed-bowl spiral mixer takes 10–15 minutes properly. For bakeries running both bread and other products from the same machine, the cleaning time between batches is a consideration.</p>

