    <h2>9. Which Mixer Should You Buy? Business-Type Recommendations</h2>

    <h3>Home Baker Scaling Up (Budget: ₹30K – ₹80K)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Planetary Mixer, 5–10 litre</strong><br>
    If you're baking cakes, cookies, and occasional bread to order from home or a small studio, a planetary mixer covers everything. At this scale, the versatility of the planetary mixer's three attachments is far more valuable than the specialisation of a spiral. A Genius or Ekon 10-litre planetary around ₹55,000–₹80,000 is the right call. Don't buy a spiral mixer at this size — it's overkill for the application and the cleaning effort isn't worth it for small batches.</p>

    <h3>Small Neighbourhood Bakery (Budget: ₹80K – ₹2L)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Planetary Mixer, 20 litre</strong><br>
    If your menu is mixed — some bread, lots of cakes, pastries, biscuits — a 20-litre planetary mixer gives you the most flexibility. A Sinmag 20-litre planetary at ₹1.2–1.5 lakh is a workhorse that handles everything. If your bread production is heavy (you're selling 200+ loaves or 500+ pav per day), add a 20-litre spiral mixer at ₹1.2–1.6 lakh. Many successful Indian bakeries at this scale run both.</p>

    <h3>Dedicated Bread Bakery (Budget: ₹1L – ₹2.5L)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Spiral Mixer, 30 litre</strong><br>
    If your business is built on bread — sourdough, artisan loaves, pav, buns, baguettes — buy a spiral mixer first. A 30-litre spiral from Sinmag or a reliable Indian brand at ₹1.5–2 lakh will serve you better than any planetary mixer for your core product. If you also need to do cakes and batters, add a small 10-litre planetary as a second machine later.</p>

    <h3>Pizzeria or Cloud Kitchen (Budget: ₹80K – ₹2L)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Spiral Mixer, 20–30 litre</strong><br>
    Pizza dough is a stiff, demanding dough that punishes planetary mixers. For a cloud kitchen making 80+ pizzas a day, a 20-litre spiral mixer is the correct and only recommendation. It will handle the load without strain, maintain dough temperature, and last significantly longer than a planetary running on pizza dough at volume.</p>

    <h3>Hotel Banquet / Large Restaurant Kitchen (Budget: ₹1.5L – ₹4L)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Planetary Mixer, 40–60 litre</strong><br>
    Hotel banquet kitchens typically have highly varied mixing needs — large batches of cake batter, cream, cookie dough, and bread dough for daily production. The planetary mixer's versatility at large volumes is the priority. A 40-litre Sinmag or Hobart planetary at ₹2–3.5 lakh handles the range. If the property has a dedicated bakery section with a bread focus, add a 60-litre spiral mixer.</p>

    <h3>Industrial / Large Commercial Bakery (Budget: ₹3L – ₹10L+)</h3>
    <p><strong>Buy: Both — Spiral for bread, Planetary for pastry</strong><br>
    At industrial scale, you shouldn't be trying to do everything with one machine. A 60-litre or 100-litre spiral mixer for bread dough production and a 40-litre or 80-litre planetary for pastry, cake, and batter work is the standard commercial bakery setup. Total investment: ₹4–8 lakh for a proper dual-mixer setup.</p>

    <h2>10. Maintenance and Lifespan</h2>
    <p>Both types of mixers are robust machines when used correctly and maintained properly. Here's what to expect:</p>

    <h3>Planetary Mixer Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Daily:</strong> Clean bowl and attachments thoroughly after use. Wipe down exterior.</li>
      <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Check and tighten bowl lift mechanism, inspect attachment shaft for wear.</li>
      <li><strong>Annually:</strong> Grease the gear mechanism (most commercial models have a sealed gearbox; some require annual greasing — check your manual).</li>
      <li><strong>Key failure point:</strong> Motor overheating from prolonged stiff dough mixing. Keep mixing times reasonable for heavy loads.</li>
      <li><strong>Expected lifespan:</strong> 8–15 years for quality brands, used correctly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Spiral Mixer Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Daily:</strong> Clean bowl and hook after each use. Check for dough buildup in the guard and base.</li>
      <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Inspect the spiral hook for wear at the welds, check the bowl rotation mechanism.</li>
      <li><strong>Annually:</strong> Gearbox service, belt/chain inspection (depending on drive type).</li>
      <li><strong>Key failure point:</strong> Bowl rotation mechanism can wear if dry dough is mixed without sufficient hydration.</li>
      <li><strong>Expected lifespan:</strong> 10–20 years for quality brands when used for bread dough.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>11. Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buying a planetary mixer for a high-volume bread operation</strong> and then wondering why the motor burns out in 18 months. This is the most common mixer mistake in Indian bakeries.</li>
      <li><strong>Undersizing the bowl.</strong> A 10-litre mixer used at 80% capacity for 12 hours a day will fail much faster than a 20-litre used at 50% capacity.</li>
      <li><strong>Buying a spiral mixer expecting it to whip cream or make cake batter.</strong> It cannot. The spiral hook does not aerate.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring spare parts availability.</strong> Always check that the brand has spare parts — particularly dough hooks, whisk wires, and bowl seals — available in India before buying.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping the service centre check.</strong> Buy a brand with a service centre in your city or within a reasonable distance. An imported mixer with no local service is a liability.</li>
    </ul>

