      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the difference between a planetary mixer and a spiral mixer? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A planetary mixer has a stationary bowl with an attachment that orbits the bowl (like a planet around the sun). It's versatile — handles batters, creams, icings, and light doughs. A spiral mixer has a rotating bowl and a fixed spiral hook that kneads dough. It's specialised for bread dough, pizza dough, and other heavy doughs. The planetary is the more versatile machine; the spiral is the better bread machine.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which mixer is best for a bakery in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">It depends on what you bake. If you make cakes, pastries, icings, and cookies — choose a planetary mixer. If you make primarily bread, pav, pizza dough, or heavy doughs — choose a spiral mixer. If you do both at scale, you need both. For most small-to-medium Indian bakeries making a mix of products, start with a 20-litre planetary mixer from Sinmag or Genius in the ₹1–1.8 lakh range.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial planetary mixer in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial planetary mixer prices in India range from ₹30,000 for a small 5-litre Indian-brand machine to ₹2.5 lakh or more for a 20-litre Hobart. The most popular mid-range option — a 20-litre Sinmag planetary mixer — costs around ₹1.2–1.5 lakh delivered in India. Indian-made 20-litre models are available from ₹80,000–₹1.2 lakh.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a spiral mixer in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Spiral mixer prices in India range from ₹60,000 for a small 10-litre Indian-brand machine to ₹4 lakh or more for a 60-litre premium European model. A 30-litre Sinmag or comparable imported spiral mixer — the most popular size for Indian bakeries — costs around ₹1.5–2 lakh. Indian-made 20-litre spiral mixers start from ₹80,000–₹1.2 lakh.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can a spiral mixer make cake batter? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">No. A spiral mixer can only knead dough — it cannot aerate batter, cream butter and sugar, or whip eggs. For cake batter, you need a planetary mixer with a flat beater or whisk attachment. If your bakery makes both bread and cakes, you need both mixer types.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I use a planetary mixer for bread dough? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, but with limitations. A planetary mixer with a dough hook can handle bread dough in small batches and for bakeries where bread is not the primary product. However, planetary mixers are not designed for heavy, continuous bread dough mixing — the motor works harder, the dough gets warmer, and the machine wears faster. For bakeries where bread is the main product, a spiral mixer is the right investment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which is the best mixer brand in India for bakeries? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For imported brands, Sinmag (Taiwan) offers the best balance of quality and price in India and is the most widely available. For premium buyers, Hobart (USA) is the gold standard. For budget buyers, Genius Baking Equipment is the most established Indian brand. For spiral mixers, Sinmag and WP Bakery are the most recommended in India.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What size mixer should I buy for my bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">As a general rule, never fill a mixer bowl beyond 60–70% of its capacity. For a small bakery making up to 50 pieces per hour, a 10–12 litre mixer is sufficient. For a medium bakery producing 100–300 pieces per hour, a 20–30 litre mixer is appropriate. For high-volume commercial production, 40–60 litre mixers are standard. Always size up rather than down — an oversized mixer is safer on the motor and more flexible for production growth.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

